Video Stitching with Timestamp Overlay (Python/OpenCV)

This Python script processes folders of timestamped .mp4 videos, converts them to grayscale, overlays vertical timestamps, skips near-black frames, and stitches them into a single output video per folder.

Features
Reads multiple .mp4 videos from a folder and sorts them by filename-based datetime.
Converts frames to grayscale.
Skips frames below a configurable brightness threshold to remove black frames.
Overlays the filename as a vertical timestamp on the bottom-left corner of each frame.
Exports a single stitched video per folder with consistent resolution and FPS.

Requirements
Python 3.x
OpenCV (cv2)

pip install opencv-python
Usage
Clone or download the script.
Update the settings at the top of the script:
parent_dir = r"D:\Transferpart2\Fentanyl"  # Root folder containing subfolders of videos
black_frame_threshold = 10                 # Mean pixel intensity threshold to skip black frames
font_scale = 0.8                           # Text size for timestamp
font_color = 255                            # Text color (0–255 for grayscale)
thickness = 2                               # Text thickness
line_height = 20                            # Vertical spacing per character
x_pos = 10                                  # Horizontal position of timestamp
bottom_margin = 10                          # Margin from bottom of frame
Run the script:
python stitch_videos_with_timestamp.py
Output files will be saved in each corresponding video folder with the naming format:
<folder_name>_stitched_output_TD.mp4
Notes
The script ignores non-directory files in the parent folder.
Videos are processed in chronological order based on their filename.
Only .mp4 files are included; hidden system files (._*) are ignored.
Timestamps are drawn vertically, one character per line, from bottom to top.
Example Folder Structure
parent_dir/
│
├── session1/
│   ├── 2026-01-01 08-00-00.mp4
│   ├── 2026-01-01 09-00-00.mp4
│
├── session2/
│   ├── 2026-01-02 08-00-00.mp4
│   └── 2026-01-02 09-00-00.mp4

Each folder will produce:

session1_stitched_output_TD.mp4
session2_stitched_output_TD.mp4
